body:
#229 added support in `flutter doctor` for determining if the developer has the Dart and Flutter IntelliJ plugins installed.

This bug tracks an enhancement to also print out version numbers of those plugins, similarily to how we do for Atom:

```
$ flutter doctor
...
[✓] Atom - a lightweight development environment for Flutter
    • flutter plugin version 0.2.4
    • dartlang plugin version 0.6.38
```

CC @danrubel

comment_data.body: @devoncarew what is the canonical way of determining the version of a .jar file?

Plugin version is specified as a `<version>` tag (child of the root `<idea-plugin>` tag) in the `plugin.xml` file. 
`plugin.xml` is in the `META-INF` folder inside the plugin JAR.
Not critical for first milestone, bumping
Yes, just not at the top of the list.
@danrubel did you have a chance to look at this one?

I just looked into this and we need to, as stated above, extract the version information from the `*.jar` file. Unfortunately, [the `package:archive` implementation](https://pub.dartlang.org/packages/archive) requires me to read the entire ~5Meg file into memory in order to extract a 2K text file from which I will extract the version information. I wish Dart had a lazy-load-from-file implementation that only read the information it needed from disk to access a single file. Maybe it does?

Doesn't look like it? https://github.com/brendan-duncan/archive/issues/12

Perhaps you could extract to a tmp dir, read the plugin.xml file, and then delete the tmp files again?

Actually reading the above again, I think it's only extracting the text file, not the full archive:

> Archive archive = new ZipDecoder().decodeBytes(zipBytes);
will decode the zip and store it in archive. However, the contents of the zip will not have been decompressed. When you access the content of a file in the Archive, such as
List jpg = archive.findFile('cat.jpg').content; then the data of that file will be decompressed on demand. The other files in the zip remain compressed until they are likewise accessed.

Correct. Its reading ~5M of compressed data into memory, then decompressing 2K from that. Still not ideal but at some point, if it becomes important, we could help update `package:archive` to read compressed data from disk on demand.
Are you sure? Lasse mentioned that zip is designed so that you can decode a zip and get the list of included files without having to read the whole archive.
No, not sure. Just glanced at the code and it seemed that's what I needed to do. Happy to have someone look over the PR above and make suggestions anytime.

title: Print out plugin version numbers
